<para id="fs-id1570525">We said that linear equations in two variables have infinitely many solutions, and we’ve just found one of them. Let’s find some other solutions to the equation <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
<example id="fs-id1596109">
<exercise id="fs-id1596111">
<problem id="fs-id1596113">
<para id="fs-id1596115">Find three more solutions to the equation <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1595516">
<title>Solution</title>
<para id="fs-id1595521">To find solutions to <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> choose a value for <m:math><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:math> or <m:math><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:math> Remember, we can choose any value we want for <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> or <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> Here we chose <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math> for <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>−3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math> for <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math><newline/>


<table id="eip-id1168468473621" class="unnumbered unstyled" summary="The figure shows three algebraic substitutions into an equation and accompanying comments. The first substitution is y = 0, with 0 shown in red The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is3 x + 2 open parentheses 0, shown in red, closed parentheses = 6. It has the comment “Substitute into the equation”. The next line is 3 x + 0 = 6. It has the comment “Simplify.” The next line is 3 x = 6. It has the comment “Solve.” The next line is x = 2. The last line is “ordered pair 0, 2”. It has the comment “Write the ordered pair.” The second substitution is x = 1, with 1 shown in blue. The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is 3 open parentheses 1, shown in blue, closed parentheses + 2 y = 6. It has the comment “Substitute into the equation”. The next line is 3 + 2 y = 6. It has the comment “Simplify.” The next line is 2 y = 3. It has the comment “Solve.” The next line is y = 3 over 2. The last line is “ordered pair 1, 3 over 2”. It has the comment “Write the ordered pair.” The third substitution is y = -3, with -3 shown in red The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is 3 x + 2 open parentheses -3, shown in red, closed parentheses = 6. It has the comment “Substitute into the equation”. The next line is 3 x -6 = 6. It has the comment “Simplify.” The next line is 3 x = 12. It has the comment “Solve.” The next line is x = 4. The last line is “ordered pair 4, -3”."><label/>
<tgroup cols="4"><tbody>

<row>
<entry valign="bottom">Substitute it into the equation.</entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1168468301681" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-01.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1168468301692" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-02.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1168468703752" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-03.png"/></media></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Simplify.
<newline/>Solve.</entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164268629147" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-04.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272182921" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-06.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272182931" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-08.png"/></media></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry/>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272182947" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-05.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272182957" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-07.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272182967" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_040_img-09.png"/></media></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Write the ordered pair.</entry>
<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:math></entry>
<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:math></entry>
<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>−3</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:math></entry>
</row>
</tbody>





</tgroup>
</table></para><para id="fs-id1569627">Check your answers.<newline/>


<table id="eip-id1168466166098" class="unnumbered unstyled" summary="The figure shows three substitutions into equations. The first starts with “ordered pair 0, 2”. The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is 3 times 2, with 2 shown in blue, + 2 times 0, with 0 shown in red = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The next line is 6 + 0 = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The last line is 6 = 6, followed by a check mark. The second substitution starts with “ordered pair 1, 3 over 2”. The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is 3 times 1, with 1 shown in blue, + 2 times 3 over 2, with 3 over 2 shown in red = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The next line is 3 + 3 = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The last line is 6 = 6, followed by a check mark.  The third substitution starts with “ordered pair 4, -3”. The next line is 3 x + 2 y = 6. The next line is 3 times 4, with 4 shown in blue, + 2 times -3, with -3 shown in red = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The next line is 12 - open parentheses -6 closed parentheses = 6, with a question mark over the equal sign. The last line is 6 = 6, followed by a check mark"><label/><tgroup cols="4">
<tbody>
<row>
