<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:math></entry>
<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>−3</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:math></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164268564770" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_041_img-01.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272147181" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_041_img-02.png"/></media></entry>
<entry><media id="eip-id1164272147192" alt="."><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_11_01_041_img-03.png"/></media></entry>
</row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table></para><para id="fs-id1569642">So <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>−3</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> are all solutions to the equation <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> In the previous example, we found that <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is a solution, too. We can list these solutions in a table.</para>
